Subject:    non-DDN domains
From:       <a href="?a=95837693600007&r=1&w=2">cbpavo.cbosgd.ATT.UUCP!mark () seismo ! CSS ! GOV (Mark Horton)</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198511">1985-11-25 0:05:35</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837667426633&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837667426633&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

We are looking into the registration of hosts in the NIC domains that
cannot be reached with TCP/IP (e.g. UUCP domains such as ATT.COM.)
There are a number of different ways to set up nameservers to handle
this.  The obvious one to use has an MF entry for ATT in COM which
just points to the gateway.

I would appreciate hearing from anyone whose mail system would break
if this were done.  I'd like to understand what would not work, and
hear suggestions for alternate ways to set this up that your mail
system can understand.  (E.g. do you really need access to a nameserver
on DDN which knows about every host all the way down the domain tree?)
Also, if your system doesn't support MF, what are your plans to upgrade it?

Thanks,

	Mark Horton
	mark@Berkeley

